WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
Ko Hikurangi te maunga, eru nei taku ngākau. Ko Whananaki te awa, e mahia nei aku māharahara.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:17.000
No Whangarei, Aotearoa, New Zealand ahau. Ka mihi au ki ngā tāngata whenua o tēnei rohe,

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:27.000
Suquamish me Duwamish me Skokoma. Ko McInnes tōku whānau, ko Tyler tōku ingoa. Kia ora!

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:36.000
Hello everyone. What you've just heard is a pepiha and this is the traditional way to make connections

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:42.000
using the indigenous language of Aotearoa called te reo Māori.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:49.000
And what this kind of translates to is saying the bones of my ancestors rest in these places

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:55.000
and it's a way for two strangers to meet and to find common ground.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:01.000
Now, confidence in embracing the indigenous language of my home country,

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:07.000
it's not something that I expected to get when last year I travelled to PositConf 2023.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:11.000
But this is one of the things that I took away from my experiences.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:15.000
In this talk I'm going to share some of my experiences from PositConf last year

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:18.000
and the things that it inspired me to do.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:23.000
So last year I came on to PositConf and it was just this incredible experience.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:28.000
You know, I was meeting all of these amazing people and they were up on stage

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:30.000
and they were talking about all of the things they were doing,

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:34.000
all the tools that they were building and the ways that they were helping people.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:40.000
And I felt really lifted up and I felt built up by this community of people.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.000
And I distinctly remember I was listening to a talk by Millie Sims

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:47.000
called The Side Effects of Blogging for a Year.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:51.000
And I wrote down, build myself a practice website.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
I knew that what I really wanted to write was blog for a year like my new idol Millie,

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:01.000
but I'm at least something of a realist so I wrote down a more modest build a practice website.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:06.000
And this was just one of a whole lot of tasks that I set myself during the talks.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.000
I was really excited and then I took my flight home.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:14.000
And let me tell you that there's nothing quite like 12 hours alone on a plane

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:16.000
to make you question things.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:19.000
I started to ask myself, you know, was this really feasible?

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:21.000
Could I get these tasks done?

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:26.000
In other words, could I convert this conference enthusiasm into action?

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:29.000
And I won't keep you in suspense.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:32.000
In a lot of cases, I didn't complete all my tasks.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.000
And I think that this is probably something that people in the audience can relate to.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:38.000
You know, we sit out with the best of intentions.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:41.000
We want to do more or we want to be better.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:46.000
And for whatever reason, we don't get everything done that we planned.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:48.000
And this can be really challenging.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:51.000
It can actually be quite a disheartening feeling.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:56.000
But I'm not disheartened because I've had some real successes in the last year.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:01.000
And the theme is that my successes all came about when I connected with my local community.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:02.000
So that's what this talk is.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:06.000
It's three short stories about things that I was inspired to do at Posit last year

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:08.000
and how I connected with my community to do so.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:12.000
And these three stories are around connecting with the indigenous language back home,

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:16.000
around starting a community-led meeting, and building a website.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:21.000
And I did all of these things in the context of my job, so I'll tell you a bit about that.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:24.000
I worked for a group called Genomics Aotearoa.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:26.000
And I might use this term Aotearoa.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:28.000
This is the indigenous name for New Zealand.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:30.000
I'll use either Aotearoa or New Zealand.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:34.000
And Genomics Aotearoa is this collaborative research platform.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:36.000
So it brings together researchers from all across the country,

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:41.000
researchers from our universities and our major research institutes,

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:45.000
brings them together to collaborate on a whole lot of diverse projects,

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:48.000
projects like working on improving local agriculture

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:53.000
or things like the sequencing of this national treasure that you can see,

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:57.000
this beautiful indigenous flightless bird, the kākāpō,

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:00.000
which turns up in the strangest of places.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:07.000
And for Genomics Aotearoa, I work as one of two bioinformatics training coordinators.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:12.000
And that means that I work with a team of people to oversee a whole series of workshops

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:14.000
to train members of the community.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:18.000
And we've had more than 1,900 people attend our workshops since 2019,

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:20.000
and that's a large number for New Zealand.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.000
And people have attended everything from like what is an R object

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:29.000
through to really specialised, focused methods on things like genome assembly.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:33.000
We build our workshops with buy-in from both the local and the international community

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:37.000
to make sure that we've got the most up-to-date skills and ideas.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:39.000
And right now we're in this really exciting phase.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:41.000
We're in the lead up to our 100th workshop,

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
and it's a milestone that we're all very excited for back home.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:48.000
All right, so that's the context of what I do and what I was doing.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
So let's take a look at some of these tasks that I set myself.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:55.000
Now, this first one looks ridiculously easy.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:58.000
Send a message to Angie Reid.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:02.000
And yes, that's Angie who we just heard from earlier in the session.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:05.000
And Angie actually spoke at PositConf 2023.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:09.000
And when she did so, she introduced herself using the language of the Penobscot people

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:11.000
with whom she'd been working so closely.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:16.000
And Angie said that this was the first time that she'd used the language to introduce herself.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:19.000
And I thought, wow, first time at a big conference.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:22.000
That takes a lot of courage and shows a real commitment.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:27.000
And Angie also said that prior to using the language,

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:29.000
she'd spoken with a local language keeper to ask,

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:31.000
is it appropriate for her to do so?

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:33.000
And the language keeper said, it is appropriate.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:35.000
It's a form of reconciliation.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:37.000
Now, this message really stood out to me.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:43.000
And so I wanted to contact Angie and say how important this was to me personally.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:45.000
But I am very shy.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:51.000
And I, you know, when it comes to contacting a stranger out of the blue over email,

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:52.000
I'm not very good at that.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:55.000
So I didn't get around to contacting Angie.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:57.000
But this message had really stuck with me.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:59.000
And so over time, my task kind of changed.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:03.000
It morphed into this idea to embrace the indigenous language and culture back home

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:08.000
and to do so in such a way that I could create a more welcoming training environment.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:11.000
Now, I knew how I could do this.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:13.000
And this was to start using karakia.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:16.000
So I should say I was already using that pepeha that you heard.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:19.000
I was using that in certain situations.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:20.000
And I learned that a little while ago.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:21.000
But I wanted to do more.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:23.000
And I wanted to start to use karakia.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:27.000
So karakia are blessings to open and close meetings.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:32.000
And they're a way to recognize, you know, the spirits and our ancestors in the environment that we're in.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:35.000
I knew that I should be using these.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:38.000
But I myself am not an indigenous person.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:40.000
I didn't grow up speaking te reo Maori.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:44.000
And I didn't grow up learning te ao Maori, the worldview.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.000
So whenever I thought about using karakia, I felt like an imposter.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:50.000
And so I wasn't sure what to do.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:53.000
But I then followed in Angie's lead.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:56.000
And I spoke to a local knowledge keeper.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:01.000
In this case, our knowledge keeper is called the Vision Matauranga Manager, Tracy Godfrey.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:05.000
And Vision Matauranga Manager, that's an employed role by Genomics Aotearoa

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:09.000
to make sure that all of the work that we do is done in consultation with

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:13.000
and in alignment with the values of indigenous Maori people.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:19.000
And Tracy, she very patiently but somewhat chidingly told me that,

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:22.000
yes, Tyler, you should be using karakia.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:24.000
And I got an opportunity.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:26.000
Coming up, we had our annual general meeting.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:30.000
And I was leading a sub-meeting within this for our early career researchers.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:34.000
And I practiced and practiced and practiced these karakia.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:37.000
On the day everybody sits down, I stand up to open the meeting.

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:41.000
And I just could not find the first word.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.000
And you might be familiar with this feeling.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:47.000
You can't force your brain to remember something in a situation.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:49.000
I see the nods. Thank you.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:51.000
I had to pull out some notes.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:53.000
And as soon as I see the first word, it was okay.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:56.000
But, you know, the whole thing was deeply embarrassing for me.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:00.000
And where did I feel like an imposter at that moment?

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:04.000
And because I'd opened the meeting with a karakia, however poorly,

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:07.000
I was obligated to close the meeting with a karakia.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:10.000
And I remember the dread of doing that close.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:14.000
When I started, the closing karakia has a call and a response.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:18.000
And a person in the audience, just one, they joined in with that response.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:21.000
And the moment they did, it shifted my perspective.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:24.000
And I was reminded, you know, this wasn't about me.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:26.000
It didn't actually really matter how I felt.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:30.000
This was about the step of reconciliation.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:34.000
And importantly, I realized that, you know, at least for one person there,

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:37.000
I had made this a more welcoming and a familiar space.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:40.000
Now, I have listed this as a task.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:43.000
Truth is, I know this isn't a task, you know, this is a journey.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:45.000
Sometimes a very challenging one to be on.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:48.000
But it's one that I'm very glad to have embarked on myself.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:51.000
And one I encourage anybody to take their first steps down.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:58.000
So the second task, all around the idea of connecting the community.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:01.000
So Aotearoa is a beautiful country.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:04.000
It's also, it's very tall and thin.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:08.000
We are extremely geographically isolated.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:09.000
You're right.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:11.000
And this applies to individuals as well.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:14.000
It's really hard to get together in person.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:19.000
And so I was thinking about this when I was listening to a talk last year

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:24.000
by Natalia Andrychuk talking about the idea of connecting the bioinformatics community at Pfizer.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:28.000
And Natalia had said that she found success by using things like Package of the Month.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:31.000
You know, you bring people together to learn about a technique,

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:33.000
but really you're connecting the community.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:36.000
And the quote that really got me was,

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:41.000
when building the community, connecting people and their experiences is vital.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:43.000
And so I wanted to do something like this.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:46.000
And I thought, right, I could start this, like, self-sustaining, self-driving meeting.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:49.000
You know, we'll have content by the community, for the community.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:51.000
It's going to be really great.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:55.000
And I got home and I thought about it a bit more and I realized, like,

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:58.000
a lot of really good people have already tried this.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:00.000
And so all of a sudden I felt very vain.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.000
Like, who am I to do this?

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:04.000
Who am I to make this succeed?

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:08.000
And I put that idea on the back burner for a little while.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:12.000
And it would have stayed there, but I had a kind of a run-in with a fellow colleague

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:15.000
and a fellow trainer, a guy called Dr. Murray Kadzow.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:18.000
We were just standing in the stairwell of all places and we were talking.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:21.000
I'd seen this piece of code and I was telling Murray I was really excited.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:23.000
And then he got really excited.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:26.000
And we said, this is all we really need to do as trainers, right?

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:28.000
We just need to get people excited about these little things,

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:32.000
the stuff that we find exciting, because data science is very cool.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:36.000
And this gave me the push and the enthusiasm to start building a little workshop.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:38.000
A really short workshop.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:40.000
I called it Publication Quality Plots with ggplot2.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:43.000
It was like, who doesn't like a nice figure to draw people in?

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:48.000
But secretly I was trying to connect people and their experiences.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.000
So I spent a long time working on this workshop.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:53.000
Now, a lot of our workshops, we run them on Zoom.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:57.000
Because of this highly dispersed community, it's easiest to bring them together on Zoom.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:01.000
And when I run a Zoom meeting, I try and run it from home

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:04.000
because my normal work environment is an active research community.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:09.000
Now, I love being part of a living, breathing, fire alarm tripping community.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:12.000
But when I'm running a Zoom meeting, it's nice to be at home

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.000
because it's a more controllable environment.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.000
So there I am. I've just done my intro.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:17.000
Everybody's ready to learn.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:20.000
And then I notice, oh, a few people are frozen.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.000
Actually, everybody's frozen.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:26.000
Oh, I have frozen.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:30.000
And I realize that I am mid-power cut.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:33.000
This is not the start that I wanted.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:36.000
So cue montage. I'm running around the house.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.000
I've got my phone in one hand. I'm texting Murray.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.000
And I'm going to put my shoes on with the other.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:43.000
I'm going to dash across town. I run up three flights of stairs.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:44.000
I sign in. I'm like...

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:48.000
And I log in and Murray is there.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:50.000
He's serenely running this meeting.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.000
And he says, I will let Tyler catch his breath.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:54.000
And he can take over with this training.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:59.000
So I'm describing this like it was a total disaster.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:01.000
And certainly to me, that is what it felt like in the moment.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:04.000
But we collected feedback.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:07.000
And our feedback said that most people were pretty happy with what they'd learned.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:09.000
They'd learned the basics of ggplot.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:10.000
That was what they really wanted.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:15.000
But I felt dejected because I felt like I'd failed in my idea

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:17.000
to connect people and their experiences.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:19.000
I needed to console myself.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:21.000
So naturally, I went down to get a coffee.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:25.000
And I opened the tearoom door to the sound of loud laughter.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:28.000
And there was my fellow trainer, Murray,

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:31.000
recounting the story of a power card.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:33.000
And sort of telling everybody how slushed I looked.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:37.000
Yeah, it's quite embarrassing.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:43.000
But, you know, we sat around and we talked a lot about workshops and training.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:45.000
As we were leaving, someone said,

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:47.000
that's actually a really good idea for another meetup.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:50.000
We'll get everybody together and we'll share our training horror stories.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.000
Because we've all got them.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:58.000
And so I don't know if this is necessarily going to become a self-sustaining community meetup.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:01.000
But right now I've got at least a little bit of community buy-in.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:04.000
All it cost was a lot of stress and a little bit of dignity.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:07.000
Which is a small price to pay.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:11.000
My last task is actually the first task I mentioned.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:14.000
And it's this one where I wanted to build a practice website.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:17.000
And I wrote this when I was listening to Millie's talk,

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:19.000
the side effects of blogging for a year.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:20.000
Hugely impactful talk for me.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
I think it was probably my favourite from the conference.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
So I wanted to build this practice website.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
And I wanted to combine this with a couple of my other tasks.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
To work on Koto.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.000
Because I'd done the Intro to Koto workshop.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:31.000
Amazing.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:35.000
And then I also wanted to communicate the success of the training program that I'm a part of.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:37.000
So I put all these together.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:40.000
And this was technically the first task that I completed.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:42.000
Now I say technically.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:47.000
Because one of the things that I really admire about GGplot and Koto.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:49.000
And the Tidyverse in general.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:51.000
Is that it's all really beautiful.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:53.000
It's also well made.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:54.000
It's admirable.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:56.000
Mine was not.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:00.000
I actually took this website down out of shame.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:03.000
I think I deleted the whole repo.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:05.000
Which is bad.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:09.000
And that would have been the very end of my Koto journey.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.000
And I wish for the sake of narrative.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
There was this lightbulb moment.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:18.000
Some critical task that required a Koto website to fix things.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:20.000
That's not really what happened.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:23.000
I guess after Posit I'd been following a lot of blogs.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:25.000
And I was following people on LinkedIn.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:28.000
And I was seeing this steady stream of high quality material.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.000
This must have been kicking around in the back of my head.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:34.000
Because at some point I wanted to find a way.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:38.000
To just kind of record all of the stuff that I do in my private life.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.000
All my hobbies and my blog.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:41.000
All my hobbies.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:45.000
And this was everything from recording stuff that I was painting for my friends.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:48.000
And data from board games that I was playing.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:51.000
And the food that I was harvesting from the garden.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:54.000
And so I built this really quick Koto website.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:56.000
Almost without thinking.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:57.000
It was very basic.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:00.000
But then I started to add different fonts.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:02.000
And I changed the background colors.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.000
Every now and then I'd reach a milestone.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.000
So I'd start a new page.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:09.000
And then I'd just sort of write down all these big ideas.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:14.000
When I realized I'd essentially been blogging for almost a year.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:17.000
And this was a really profound moment for me.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:22.000
Because it didn't matter that this particular blog only has a viewership of one.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:27.000
For me this was a task that I had said don't try this.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:29.000
Don't even write this down.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:31.000
And yet I made this thing.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:36.000
And I did it entirely on the back of the enthusiasm from my online community.

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:38.000
Which was really important.

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:44.000
So I would never under any circumstances show anyone my private hobby blog.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:47.000
But I would like it if you'd take a look at this.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.000
It's a work in progress.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:53.000
This is a website that I'm building to communicate the training program that I'm a part of.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:55.000
So you can take a look at this.

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:58.000
You can learn a bit more about the work that we do.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:00.000
You can learn about Genomics Aotearoa.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.000
And you can meet the training team itself.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.000
I've got sort of LinkedIn details for all of the team members.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:08.000
This QR code is repeated at the end as well, by the way.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:09.000
Okay.

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:11.000
So what am I trying to say with this talk?

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:13.000
Well, there are two things.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:17.000
And the first is that conferences are so much more than knowledge sharing.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:19.000
They're an opportunity for us to connect with one another.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:21.000
To feel excited.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:24.000
To sort of get built up by the community around us.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:27.000
And that's amazing.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:31.000
Conferences are a real luxury.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:33.000
They're not our day-to-day reality.

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:40.000
And I think that it's only when we come home and we reconnect with the people who we see on a day-to-day basis.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.000
They're the ones who laugh at us.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:44.000
They're the ones who pick us up when we're down.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:48.000
And it's with the people who are closest to us that we really reaffirm what's important to us.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:52.000
And it's through them that we tend to achieve our goals.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:58.000
Now, I'll use that sort of message around my local community to segue into my last slide.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:01.000
Where I repeat this photo of the team of people that I work with.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:03.000
Acknowledging both the company that I work for.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:05.000
Our close partners.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:08.000
The New Zealand eScience infrastructure.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:11.000
And you've got some links that you can use to look at our website.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:13.000
To meet the rest of the team.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:15.000
And connect with me on LinkedIn if you'd like.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:16.000
Thank you.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:17.000
Thank you.

